<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="58" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,505,1214]" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,757,782]" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gressitt, J. L." box="[322,491,757,782]" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences" pageId="8" pageNumber="58" pagination="433 - 592" part="27" refString="Gressitt, J. L. (1952) The tortoise beetles of China (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae). Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, 27, 433 - 592, pls 1 - 36." title="The tortoise beetles of China (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae)" type="journal article" year="1952">Gressitt (1952)</bibRefCitation>
stated that the 
<typeStatus box="[661,759,757,782]" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">holotype</typeStatus>
is in 
<collectionCode box="[821,878,758,782]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15690" name="California Academy of Sciences" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">CAS</collectionCode>
, however, there is no such specimen. Because the 
<collectionCode box="[151,234,794,817]" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">LMHN</collectionCode>
specimen agrees with the locality data and posses the original Gressittʼs labels it should be the original 
<typeStatus box="[151,253,829,854]" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">holotype</typeStatus>
. It particularly agrees with the description in its artificially pale colouration being result of its teneral nature and colouration of fully sclerotized specimen would be much darker. Gressitt separated this species by the width of pronotum being equal to span of humeral angles. 
<bibRefCitation author="Chen, S. &amp; Yu, P. &amp; Sun, C. &amp; Tʼan, C. &amp; Zia, Y." bookContentInfo="653 pp." box="[830,1040,901,926]" journalOrPublisher="Science Press, Beijing, xv" pageId="8" pageNumber="58" refString="Chen, S., Yu, P., Sun, C., Tʼan, C. &amp; Zia, Y. (1986) Fauna Sinica. Insecta. Coleoptera Hispidae. Science Press, Beijing, xv + 653 pp. + 15 pls." title="Fauna Sinica. Insecta. Coleoptera Hispidae" type="book" year="1986">
Chen 
<emphasis box="[898,957,901,926]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">et al.</emphasis>
(1986)
</bibRefCitation>
synonymized 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gressitt" authorityYear="1952" box="[1209,1342,901,926]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cassida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laticollis">
<emphasis box="[1209,1342,901,926]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">C. laticollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1866" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cassida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscorufa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">C. fuscorufa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The latter is a very variable species and in addition the proportion of the width of the pronotum and the elytra is sexually dimorphic. The 
<typeStatus box="[527,625,973,998]" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">holotype</typeStatus>
has weakly convex elytra and is fully within instraspecific variability of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1866" box="[151,289,1010,1034]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cassida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscorufa">
<emphasis box="[151,289,1010,1034]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">C. fuscorufa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,505,1214]" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">
The 
<typeStatus box="[251,299,1046,1070]" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">type</typeStatus>
locality refers to Shuishaba village situated approximately in the middle of the Shuishaba valley in the Lichuan district and the specimen was collected during the expedition lead by Gressitt to explore Dawn- Redwood (
<taxonomicName authority="Hu &amp; W. C. Cheng" authorityName="Hu &amp; W.C.Cheng" box="[280,849,1117,1142]" class="Pinopsida" family="Cupressaceae" genus="Metasequoia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="8" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="glyptostroboides">
<emphasis box="[280,623,1117,1142]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">Metasequoia glyptostroboides</emphasis>
Hu &amp; W.C.Cheng
</taxonomicName>
), for details see 
<bibRefCitation author="Gressitt, J. L." box="[1053,1243,1117,1142]" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences" pageId="8" pageNumber="58" pagination="25 - 58" part="28" refString="Gressitt, J. L. (1953 b) The California Academy-Lingnan Dawn-Redwood Expedition. Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, 28, 25 - 58." title="The California Academy-Lingnan Dawn-Redwood Expedition" type="journal article" year="1953" yearSuffix="b">Gressitt (1953b)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Chu, K. - L. &amp; Cooper, W. S." journalOrPublisher="Ecology" pageId="8" pageNumber="58" pagination="260 - 278" part="31" publicationUrl="http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/1932391" refString="Chu, K. - L. &amp; Cooper, W. S. (1950) An ecological reconnaissance in the native home of Metasequoia glyptostroboides. Ecology, 31, 260 - 278. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.2307 / 1932391" title="An ecological reconnaissance in the native home of Metasequoia glyptostroboides" type="journal article" year="1950">Chu &amp; Cooper (1950)</bibRefCitation>
published a rough map of the Shuishaba valley (as Shui-hsa-pa), however, the coordinates seems to be quite off the true place hence are not accepted here. Exact geographic position of the 
<typeStatus box="[1042,1090,1190,1214]" pageId="8" pageNumber="58">type</typeStatus>
locality is unknown to us.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
